SIMPLE: priest
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Priest
<hw>Priest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>prest</ets>,
<ets>preost</ets>, AS. <ets>pre⟦oacute⟧st</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>presbyter</ets>, Gr. <?/ elder, older, n., an elder, compar. of <?/
an old man, the first syllable of which is probably akin to L.
<ets>pristinus</ets>. Cf. <er>Pristine</er>,
<er>Presbyter</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1137 --></p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Christian Church)</fld> <def>A presbyter elder; a
minister</def>; specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(R. C. Ch. & Gr.
Ch.)</fld> <def>One who is authorized to consecrate the host and to say
Mass; but especially, one of the lowest order possessing this
power.</def> <au>Murdock.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Ch. of Eng. & Prot.
Epis. Ch.)</fld> <def>A presbyter; one who belongs to the intermediate
order between bishop and deacon. He is authorized to perform all
ministerial services except those of ordination and
confirmation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who officiates at the altar, or performs the
rites of sacrifice; one who acts as a mediator between men and the
divinity or the gods in any form of religion; <as>as, Buddhist
<ex>priests</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>priests</xex> of
Dagon.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>1 Sam. v. 5.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then the <qex>priest</qex> of Jupiter . . . brought oxen and
garlands . . . and would have done sacrifice with the people.</q>
<au>Acts xiv. 13.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every <qex>priest</qex> taken from among men is ordained for men
in things pertaining to God, that he may offer both gifts and sacrifices
for sins.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. v. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the New Testament presbyters are not called
<xex>priests</xex>; but Christ is designated as a <xex>priest</xex>, and
as a high <xex>priest</xex>, and all Christians are designated
<xex>priests</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Priest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Priest
<hw>Priest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To ordain as
priest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Priestcap</ent>⟦br⟧
